label school_plague_history1:
    history "So, how many people were infected by the Plague? In more urban areas the infection rate was as much as 85%% of the population. Much lower in more rural areas. And lower still in less developed countries."
    history "The mortality rate depended on the overall health of the person infected."
    history "In the more developed world the mortality rate was extremely high due to a larger elderly population, poor or fatty diets and people with serious conditions treated by modern medicine."
    history "In a nutshell, anyone who was not at peak physical health was considered high risk. As you can imagine that was the majority of the population. So many nations, including ours, saw as much as a 40-50%% decline in the population."
    history "For some of the more populated nations, that means the number of deaths was well over 100 million. A staggering number of lives lost. And the most lives lost at any point in human history."
    history "With that piece of knowledge, you can see how society changed so much."
    history "Many of you might watch shows or movies made before the Plague and wonder if that world even existed. Yes it did, but it does not exist anymore."
    history "With all that out of the way, next lesson we will discuss how it started and continue on from there until we reach where we are now today."
