    jump school_class_lesson_end

label school_plague_history2:
    history "To start with how the Plague started and spread, we first need to talk about the Coronavirus that preceded it. It was a serious pandemic that started 2 years before the Plague."
    history "It is generally believed, but not proven to, have started in China, then slowly spread worldwide. The reason the Coronavirus is important to the topic of the Plague is because of how people reacted."
    history "The Coronavirus had impacted many people's lives for almost two years. Self isolation, quarantine, over burdened hospitals. It tipped people's way of life on it's head."
    history "And as the world started to recover, both economically and socially, a new disease was being noticed. What do you think people did about the news of such a thing?"
    history "For the most part, nothing. People were tired or fed up. They just wanted their normal way of life back. This new disease was widely ignored even after countries like Greece, Turkey and Egypt went into full lockdown."
    history "Many of the failures of the Coronavirus were repeated. The economy was prioritised over lives, action was delayed and politicians couldn't agree if there even was a problem."
    history "This lead to the Plague being spread worldwide, much like the Coronavirus. But with much more dire consequences."
    $ school_plague_history += 1
    jump school_class_lesson_end

label school_plague_history3:
    history "And so the Plague spread worldwide. Most countries reimplemented the lockdown procedures learned from the Coronavirus. But unfortunately, what could be considered an even worse plague was spreading."
    history "Misinformation and propaganda. From the Coronavirus, a large amount of conspiracy theories and misinformation had spread. News of a new pandemic made a lot of people believe such things to be true."
    history "Many people found it impossible to believe there could suddenly be two pandemics and so bought into the conspiracy theories."
    history "There were far too many conspiracies circulating. Ranging from believable to outright insane. But we won't go into any of those here."
    history "What it did mean is that large portions of the population were not self isolating, social distancing or taking other basic precautions such as increased hygiene standards."
    history "Combine that with the significantly higher transmission rate of the Plague, and a higher mortality rate, it was not very long before governments had to start using mass graves or incineration plants."
    history "Finally the conspiracies started to die down once people were able to actually observe with their own eyes the effect the Plague was having. But at this point it was already far too late."
    $ school_plague_history += 1
    jump school_class_lesson_end

label school_plague_history4:
    history "After massive deaths caused by the Plague, governments started to implement very strict procedures to combat its spread. Many going as far as declaring martial law nationwide."
    history "For some nations, even in the developed world, going outside could get you shot. Such was the measures put in place towards the end."
    history "This lead to many deaths caused indirectly by the Plague. Not just being shot, but not being able to go outside meant you had no access to food or other amenities."
    history "Lack of food caused mass protests which quickly turned into riots and looting. This caused the military and police forces to pull back and create \"Safe zones\" in the cities. Of course in the wealthy areas."
    history "As you can imagine, this caused outrage and there were many clashes at safe zone checkpoints. People were starving, and it was presumed correctly that there were food storages inside the safe zones."
    history "Eventually some of the safe zones were breached and the militaries fired on the interlopers causing more deaths and outrage."
    history "Finally the fires died down once a vaccine was announced to have been found and mass production was being prepared."
    $ school_plague_history += 1
    jump school_class_lesson_end

label school_plague_history5:
    history "Once a Plague vaccine was announced, things calmed down a little, but tensions were still high."
    history "People were starving, the economy of almost every major nation in the world had collapsed and the rich still had food."
    history "In their hurry to try to calm the populace, many governments either turned to the military for security or to corporations to solve the food crisis."
    history "Both of these \"solutions\" ended poorly for most. In the countries that turned to the military, they quickly turned into military dictatorships. With the government and police forces being disbanded."
    history "In our case where the corporations were looked to for a solution, we fared a little better. Instead now the country is mostly run by a cabal of the wealthy with a puppet government installed."
    history "Time will tell how our new government system will pan out. But in our current recovery period it's clear that we will never return to the world that existed before the Coronavirus."
    $ school_plague_history += 1
    jump school_class_lesson_end

